      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay but when you say \"most experts agree,\" it feels like you're basically saying the deterrence argument is just wrong or outdated. isn't it possible that the issue isn't that the theory is \"weak,\" but just that it's being implemented poorly? it feels like you're siding with the reformist view rather than staying neutral. can't we just say that both approaches have valid goals and different ways of measuring success?",
