      "content": "I agree that many \"tough on crime\" policies are implemented poorly, which often leads to incarceration spikes without corresponding drops in crime rates. While deterrence can work theoretically, the real-world data shows that heavy penalties rarely deter most offenders and instead often exacerbate the very problems like poverty and lack of opportunity that drive crime. Therefore, it's not a question of whether zero tolerance has goals, but rather that evidence-based approaches focusing on prevention and rehabilitation consistently yield better long-term safety outcomes than punitive measures alone.",
